'''''Candida theae''''' is a species of [[yeast]] in the genus ''[[Candida (fungus)|Candida]]''.  The species name means "tea".<ref name="Chicha">{{cite web |url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=new-species-resurrected-ancient-andean-tomb |title=Raising the Dead: New Species of Life Resurrected from Ancient Andean Tomb |first=R. Douglas |last=Fields |date=19 February 2012 |website=Scientific American |publisher=Scientific American |location=New York, NY |accessdate=24 February 2012 |quote=But careful genetic analysis showed that two strains of yeast were a new species of Candida, which he named C. theae, meaning "tea."}}</ref>  It was first isolated from [[Indonesia]]n [[tea]] drinks<ref name="spnov" /> and in [[Quito]] from clay pots that contained [[chicha]] dating from 680 [[Common Era|CE]].<ref name="Chicha" />

